            "Arduino",
            "Android phone",
            "USB Host Controller (if sketch does not upload)"
        ],
        "description": "This project aims to create a portable Arduino setup by replacing the standard USB Type-B connector with a Micro USB OTG connector, enabling programming via a smartphone. This modification allows the Arduino to be powered and programmed without a laptop, enhancing its portability and convenience for on-the-go projects.",
        "steps": [
            "Disassemble the USB Type-B cable by peeling off the rubber seal, opening the cable clamp, and removing the plastic case from the metal case.",
            "Disassemble the Micro USB connector by peeling off the rubber or plastic case, exposing the five pins (Vcc, Data-, Data+, ID, Ground). If necessary, cut off any vertical lines after the cable soldering pads to separate the rear of the connector.",
            "Test the continuity of the Micro USB connector pins with a multimeter to identify any short circuits. Correct any shorts by cutting off the problematic pins.",
            "Solder the Micro USB connector pins to the corresponding USB Type-B connector wires (Vcc to Vcc, Data- to Data-, Data+ to Data+, Ground to Ground). Connect the ID pin (pin 4) of the Micro USB to Ground (pin 5).",
            "Re-check all connections with a multimeter using the continuity test to ensure perfect connections and no short circuits.",
            "Tape the metal case of the USB Type-B connector to prevent short circuits. Insert the modified Micro USB connector into the Type-B metal case.",
            "Use a hot glue gun to fill any gaps in the connector, securing the wires and connections in place. Allow the glue to dry completely.",
            "Upload a sketch to the Arduino using a smartphone and the ArduinoDroid app. If the sketch fails to upload, install a USB Host Controller."
        ]
